## Upstream lineage

### WSJT-X — Joe Taylor (K1JT) and the WSJT Development Group
License: **GNU GPL, version 3 or later** (GPLv3-or-later).

Nexus's modem library, `libft1/`, is derived from WSJT-X. The WSJT-X-derived
modem source that `libft1` compiles is **vendored in this repository** as the
complete corresponding source (GPL-3.0 §6) at **`libft1/vendor/wsjtx/`** — a
subset of WSJT-X's `lib/` (the ~70 DSP sources actually compiled; no Qt/GUI).
The build uses it by default, so a fresh clone rebuilds the modem with no
external checkout. See `libft1/vendor/wsjtx/README.md` for provenance and for
which files are original FT1 code vs. reused/modified WSJT-X. From WSJT-X,
`libft1` reuses:

- the **77-bit message packing/unpacking** (`packjt77`, used via `unpack77`
  in `libft1/ft1_cabi.f90`), so Chat / QSO / Field Day forms carry the same
  77-bit payloads on either tier;
- the **LDPC(174,91) codec** — `encode174_91` and the `bpdecode174_91`
  soft-decision belief-propagation decoder;
- the **CRC-14** message check (`chkcrc14a.f90` plus `crc14.cpp`);
- the **`four2a` FFT** routine and surrounding DSP infrastructure that
  `libft1` reuses (alongside FFTW3, below).

WSJT-X is the work of Joe Taylor (K1JT) and the WSJT Development Group,
including Steve Franke (K9AN), Bill Somerville (G4WJS), Nico Palermo (IV3NWV),
Uwe Risse (DG2YCB), Brian Moran (N9ADG), and others. See the upstream project
for the authoritative copyright and contributor list:
https://sourceforge.net/projects/wsjt/

Nexus treats WSJT-X as the reference standard for FT8/FT4 on-air behavior. It
is an independent application and is **not affiliated with or endorsed by** the
WSJT project.

### FT1 waveform — KD9TAW
License: **GPL-3.0-or-later** (part of Nexus / `libft1`).

The FT1 waveform (the 4-CPM coherent turbo modem with IR-HARQ used by the
"Fast" tier) is original work by KD9TAW. The DX1 mode (`libft1/dx1/` — the
non-coherent 8-FSK + soft LDPC(174,91) "Robust" tier) is likewise authored by
KD9TAW. Both are GPLv3 by virtue of the shared WSJT-X-derived code they build
on.

> Validation status: **FT8/FT4** is the production digital core — operational
> parity with stock WSJT-X behavior, wire formats pinned, field-verified.
> **FT1 and DX1** are the new native waveforms and are **simulation-validated
> only** (AWGN, with a fading penalty modeled); they have **not** yet been
> validated on the air. Published Windows binaries are cross-compiled beta
> builds.

