## Bundled components (shipped in the Windows installer)

### Hamlib (rigctld)
License: **GPL-2.0 / LGPL-2.1** — see upstream project. Hamlib ships its own
license texts with the binaries; the staging script
(`scripts/fetch-hamlib.sh`) places them, along with `rigctld.exe`,
`rigctl.exe`, and the required DLLs, under
`src-tauri/resources/hamlib/`, which the Tauri bundle then includes
(`tauri.conf.json` → `bundle.resources`). Nexus launches the bundled
`rigctld` for offline CAT rig control. The Hamlib binaries are **not committed
to this repository** — `scripts/fetch-hamlib.sh` reproduces them from the
official Hamlib release. Refer to the license files shipped under
`resources/hamlib/` (and the Hamlib project) for exact terms.

### DXCC country file (cty.dat) — Jim Reisert, AD1C
`crates/propagation/data/cty.dat` is the AD1C "Country Files" (the big-CTY
`cty.dat` database) by Jim Reisert, **AD1C** (<https://www.country-files.com/>),
embedded verbatim (via `include_str!`, see `crates/propagation/src/dxcc.rs`).
It resolves callsigns to DXCC entities and CQ/ITU zones and underpins the
DXCC / WAS / WAZ awards engine, map spot labels, and Needed-board hints. It is
distributed under the **MIT License**. © 1994– Jim Reisert AD1C. See
`crates/propagation/data/cty.dat_copyright.txt`.

### ITU-R / CCIR propagation coefficient data
The HF path-prediction engine embeds the CCIR ionospheric numerical-map
coefficients (foF2, M(3000)F2, foE, sporadic-E) and the Recommendation
ITU-R P.372 atmospheric-noise coefficient arrays, plus the P.1239-3
day-to-day variability deciles, copied verbatim from the ITU-R Study Group 3
reference implementation of Recommendation ITU-R P.533
(<https://github.com/ITU-R-Study-Group-3/ITU-R-HF>). These are the
long-published ITU-R/CCIR data that accompany every P.533/VOACAP
implementation. Files + full provenance note:
`crates/propagation/data/itu/` (see `itu_copyright.txt`). The P.533 engine
itself (`crates/propagation/src/p533/`) is an original Rust implementation of
the published Recommendation methods; no ITU code is included.

### Natural Earth geography (grid-rarity table)
`crates/propagation/data/grid_rarity.bin` (8.1 KB) is derived from the
Natural Earth 1:10m land polygons (via the `world-atlas` package), which are
**public domain**. Regenerate with `scripts/gen-grid-rarity.mjs`.

### WAS grid-square → US-state table (grid_state.bin)
`crates/propagation/data/grid_state.bin` (32,400 bytes, embedded via
`include_bytes!`) maps each 4-character Maidenhead grid to a US state for the
Worked-All-States "New State" need hint. It is generated
(`scripts/gen-grid-state.mjs`) by point-in-polygon sampling of the
**`us-atlas`** `states-10m` TopoJSON
(<https://github.com/topojson/us-atlas>, ISC-licensed package), whose geometry
derives from **US Census Bureau** cartographic boundary files (a work of the
US government, **public domain**). Regenerate with
`node scripts/gen-grid-state.mjs`.

### CQ zone boundaries
`ui/src/data/cqzones.geojson` is from HB9HIL's hamradio-zones-geojson
(<https://github.com/HB9HIL/hamradio-zones-geojson>), **MIT** (© 2024 HB9HIL);
the license text ships beside it (`cqzones.LICENSE.txt`).

### World Magnetic Model coefficients (WMM2025)
`crates/propagation/data/WMM_2025.COF` is the official WMM2025 coefficient
file produced by NOAA/NCEI and the British Geological Survey. As a work of
the US government it is **public domain**; the model is valid 2025.0–2030.0.
The declination evaluator (`crates/propagation/src/wmm.rs`) is an original
implementation validated against the official WMM2025 test-value table.

